<div class="description">
    <h3>Description</h3>

    <div class="body">
        <p>Currently, Zend_Cache_Core performs cache ID validation and only allows [a-zA-Z0-9_], whilst cache backends such as memcached can support cache IDs with other characters (e.g. dashes and colons).</p>

<p>This issue becomes a problem, for example, if a developer wanted to share sessions via memcached with a Ruby on Rails application which supports and writes it's cache IDs with colon characters.  So I imagine that this issue could potentially be a block whenever trying to utilize cache data written by applications that allow all the cache ID characters (aside from [a-zA-Z0-9_]) supported by a specific caching backend.</p>

